            "type": "link",
            "rel": null,
            "target": null,
            "title": null,
            "url": "https://www.vox.com/2021/4/5/22367832/senate-democrats-budget-reconciliation-filibuster",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": " that they can pass more bills using budget reconciliation, a convoluted process that allows bills related to spending to pass with a simple 51-vote majority, rather than the 60 votes usually needed to end the opposing party’s filibuster and move legislation to a vote. That may sound like good news, since Democrats only have 51 reliable votes in the Senate, but the process cannot be used to pass many of the party’s key priorities into law.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Just last month, Democrats passed a COVID-19 relief bill that excluded a promised $15 minimum wage because the parliamentarian, Elizabeth MacDonough, said the measure wasn’t a budget item and shouldn’t be part of a reconciliation bill. Democrats could have ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "children": [
              {
                "detail": 0,
                "format": 0,
                "mode": "normal",
                "style": "",
                "text": "overruled the parliamentarian",
                "type": "text",
                "version": 1
              }
            ],
            "direction": "ltr",
            "format": "",
            "indent": 0,
            "type": "link",
            "rel": null,
            "target": null,
